[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 6.8: Disease Subtype Discovery
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Research/Clinical Validation · **Estimated Cost:** ~$200-2,000/month (depending on dataset size and compute)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Here's a scenario that plays out in every major health system's research department. A pulmonologist has 4,000 patients with a diagnosis of "COPD." She treats them all roughly the same way: bronchodilators, inhaled corticosteroids, pulmonary rehab referrals. Some patients respond beautifully. Some don't respond at all. Some get worse despite textbook-perfect treatment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m She suspects there are actually three or four different diseases hiding under the single "COPD" label. Different underlying mechanisms, different progression patterns, different treatment responses. But the ICD-10 code is the same for all of them. The clinical taxonomy says they're one disease. Her gut says otherwise.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This isn't a hypothetical. It's the story of how asthma went from one disease to a dozen recognized endotypes (allergic, eosinophilic, neutrophilic, exercise-induced, aspirin-exacerbated). It's how breast cancer went from one disease to at least four molecular subtypes with radically different treatment protocols. It's how Type 2 diabetes is increasingly understood as a cluster of metabolic phenotypes rather than a single condition.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The problem is that discovering these subtypes takes decades when done through traditional clinical observation. A researcher notices a pattern, publishes a case series, other researchers replicate, consensus builds, guidelines change. That cycle takes 10-20 years from first observation to standard-of-care change.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Unsupervised clustering on large clinical datasets can compress that timeline dramatically. Not by replacing clinical judgment, but by surfacing candidate subtypes that clinicians can then validate. The machine finds the patterns. The humans decide if the patterns are real and clinically meaningful.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The stakes are high. If you discover a genuine subtype with a different treatment response, you've potentially changed outcomes for thousands of patients. If you discover a statistical artifact and publish it, you've wasted everyone's time and eroded trust in computational approaches. The difference between those two outcomes is entirely about validation rigor.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Unsupervised Clustering for Subtype Discovery
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What Unsupervised Clustering Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Supervised learning needs labels. You tell the algorithm "these patients have disease X, these don't" and it learns to distinguish them. Unsupervised clustering has no labels. You hand it a pile of patient feature vectors and say "find groups." It organizes patients into clusters based on similarity in the feature space, without any prior knowledge of what the groups should be.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is both the power and the danger. The power: you can discover structure that nobody knew existed. The danger: the algorithm will always find clusters, even in random noise. It has no concept of "there are no meaningful groups here." It will happily partition random data into neat-looking clusters and report high confidence.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The core algorithms you'll encounter in this space:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **K-means** is the simplest. It partitions data into K groups by minimizing within-cluster variance. Fast, scalable, interpretable. But it assumes spherical clusters of roughly equal size, which biological data almost never produces. It also requires you to specify K in advance, which is the thing you're trying to discover.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Gaussian Mixture Models (GMMs)** are more flexible. They model each cluster as a Gaussian distribution with its own mean and covariance, allowing elliptical clusters of different sizes. They also give you soft assignments (probability of belonging to each cluster) rather than hard assignments, which is more honest about the uncertainty.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hierarchical clustering** builds a tree (dendrogram) of nested clusters. You can cut the tree at different levels to get different numbers of clusters. Useful for exploring structure at multiple granularities. Computationally expensive for large datasets.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **DBSCAN and HDBSCAN** find clusters of arbitrary shape based on density. They can identify outliers (points that don't belong to any cluster). Useful when subtypes have irregular boundaries in feature space. HDBSCAN is the hierarchical variant that handles varying densities better.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Spectral clustering** works by constructing a similarity graph and finding clusters in the graph's spectral embedding. Good for non-convex cluster shapes. Computationally expensive but powerful for complex structure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Deep clustering** (autoencoders + clustering) learns a low-dimensional representation and clusters simultaneously. Useful when the raw feature space is very high-dimensional and the meaningful structure lives in a learned manifold. More powerful but harder to interpret.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why This Is Harder Than It Sounds
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The fundamental challenge of disease subtype discovery isn't the clustering algorithm. It's everything around it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Feature selection determines your results.** If you cluster on lab values, you'll find lab-value-based subtypes. If you cluster on genomic data, you'll find genomic subtypes. If you cluster on utilization patterns, you'll find utilization subtypes. The features you choose implicitly define what "subtype" means. This requires deep clinical input. A statistician alone cannot make this decision.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The number of clusters is unknown.** Unlike supervised problems where you have a clear target, here you're asking "how many subtypes exist?" The answer depends on your resolution. At one level, there might be 3 subtypes. Zoom in on one of those and there might be 2 sub-subtypes. There's no single correct answer. Methods like the elbow method, silhouette scores, gap statistics, and Bayesian information criterion (BIC) provide guidance, but they often disagree with each other.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Stability matters more than fit.** A clustering solution that changes dramatically when you remove 10% of the data is not discovering real structure. It's fitting noise. Stability analysis (bootstrap resampling, cross-validation of cluster assignments) is essential and often skipped.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Clinical validation is the real test.** Statistical clusters are not disease subtypes until clinicians confirm they're clinically meaningful. Do the clusters have different prognoses? Different treatment responses? Different biomarker profiles? If the clusters are statistically clean but clinically indistinguishable, they're not subtypes. They're artifacts.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Confounders hide everywhere.** Age, sex, race, socioeconomic status, and site-of-care all create structure in clinical data. If your clusters are really just "young patients vs. old patients" or "patients at Hospital A vs. Hospital B," you haven't discovered subtypes. You've rediscovered demographics. Careful confounder analysis is non-negotiable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The last five years have seen significant progress in making subtype discovery more rigorous:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Consensus clustering** runs the clustering algorithm many times with different random seeds, subsamples, or parameter settings, then builds a consensus matrix showing how often each pair of patients ends up in the same cluster. Pairs that are always together (or never together) represent robust structure. Pairs that flip between clusters represent uncertainty.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-omics integration** combines clinical, genomic, proteomic, and imaging data into unified clustering frameworks. Methods like Similarity Network Fusion (SNF) and Multi-Omics Factor Analysis (MOFA) handle the heterogeneity of different data types.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Interpretable clustering** has become a priority. It's not enough to find clusters. You need to explain what makes each cluster different in terms that clinicians can act on. Decision tree surrogates, SHAP-based cluster explanations, and characteristic feature identification are now standard practice.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Temporal clustering** recognizes that disease subtypes may not be static. A patient might transition between subtypes over time. Hidden Markov Models and trajectory clustering capture this dynamic structure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The pipeline for disease subtype discovery has more stages than a typical ML pipeline because of the validation requirements:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Data Assembly] → [Feature Engineering] → [Dimensionality Reduction] → [Clustering] → [Stability Assessment] → [Clinical Characterization] → [Validation] → [Reporting]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Data Assembly.** Pull together the clinical dataset: structured EHR data (labs, vitals, diagnoses, medications, procedures), possibly unstructured data (NLP-extracted features from notes), possibly genomic or imaging features. Define the cohort (which patients, what time window, what inclusion/exclusion criteria). This step alone can take weeks.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Feature Engineering.** Transform raw clinical data into meaningful features. Aggregate labs over time (mean, trend, variability). Encode medications as binary or categorical features. Handle missing data (a major challenge in clinical datasets; missingness itself can be informative). Normalize features to comparable scales.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Dimensionality Reduction.** Clinical feature spaces are often high-dimensional (hundreds of features). Clustering in high dimensions suffers from the curse of dimensionality (distances become meaningless). Reduce to a meaningful lower-dimensional space using PCA, UMAP, autoencoders, or domain-guided feature selection. This step also helps with visualization.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Clustering.** Apply one or more clustering algorithms. Run consensus clustering to assess robustness. Evaluate multiple values of K. Compare results across algorithms. If different algorithms find similar structure, that's a good sign.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Stability Assessment.** Bootstrap the dataset (resample with replacement) and re-cluster. How stable are the assignments? Use metrics like Adjusted Rand Index (ARI) between bootstrap runs. Clusters that are stable across resampling are more likely to represent real structure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Clinical Characterization.** For each discovered cluster, characterize it clinically. What are the distinguishing features? What's the demographic profile? What are the outcomes (mortality, hospitalization, treatment response)? This is where you go from "statistical cluster" to "candidate subtype."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Validation.** The critical step. Validate on a held-out cohort or external dataset. Do the same clusters appear? Do they have the same clinical characteristics? If the clusters don't replicate, they're not real subtypes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Reporting.** Generate interpretable reports for clinical collaborators. Visualizations (UMAP plots, heatmaps, survival curves by cluster), characteristic features per cluster, and statistical comparisons. This is what goes into the publication or the clinical review meeting.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon SageMaker for the ML pipeline.** Subtype discovery involves iterative experimentation: trying different feature sets, different algorithms, different K values, different preprocessing choices. SageMaker provides managed Jupyter notebooks for exploration, training jobs for compute-intensive clustering runs, and processing jobs for data transformation. The experiment tracking (SageMaker Experiments) is essential here because you'll run dozens of variations and need to compare them systematically.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon S3 for data lake storage.** Clinical datasets for subtype discovery are large (thousands to millions of patients, hundreds of features) and need to be versioned. S3 provides durable, encrypted storage with versioning. You'll store raw extracts, processed feature matrices, clustering results, and validation outputs. The lifecycle here is research-oriented: you need to go back to earlier versions when a reviewer asks "what happens if you exclude patients with less than 6 months of data?"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Glue for ETL.** Assembling the clinical dataset from multiple source systems (EHR, claims, labs, pharmacy) requires substantial data transformation. Glue handles the joins, aggregations, and feature engineering at scale. Glue Data Catalog provides schema management for the evolving feature sets.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Athena for ad-hoc exploration.** Before you cluster, you need to understand your data. Athena lets you run SQL queries directly against S3 data to explore distributions, check for missingness patterns, and validate cohort definitions without spinning up infrastructure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Neptune (optional) for relationship modeling.** If your subtype discovery incorporates comorbidity networks or medication interaction graphs, Neptune provides a graph database for modeling these relationships. Not every subtype discovery project needs this, but it's powerful for multi-morbidity pattern analysis.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m flowchart TD
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     A[Clinical Data Sources\nEHR / Claims / Labs / Genomics] -->|Extract| B[S3 Data Lake\nRaw Zone]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     B -->|Glue ETL| C[S3 Data Lake\nProcessed Zone\nFeature Matrices]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|Load| D[SageMaker Notebook\nExploration & Feature Selection]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     D -->|Submit| E[SageMaker Training Jobs\nClustering Algorithms]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     E -->|Results| F[S3 Results Zone\nCluster Assignments]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     F -->|Analyze| G[SageMaker Notebook\nStability & Validation]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     G -->|Characterize| H[Clinical Reports\nSubtype Profiles]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     I[Athena] -->|Query| C
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     J[SageMaker Experiments] -->|Track| E
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style B fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style E fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style F fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon SageMaker, Amazon S3, AWS Glue, Amazon Athena, AWS KMS |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `sagemaker:CreateTrainingJob`, `sagemaker:CreateProcessingJob`, `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `glue:StartJobRun`, `athena:StartQueryExecution` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **BAA** | AWS BAA signed (clinical data contains PHI) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS; SageMaker: volume encryption with KMS; Athena: encrypted query results; all transit over TLS |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | SageMaker notebooks and training jobs in private subnets with VPC endpoints for S3, SageMaker API, and CloudWatch Logs |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled: log all data access for HIPAA audit trail |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Data Governance** | IRB approval for research use; data use agreement if multi-site; de-identification or limited dataset per HIPAA research provisions |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Sample Data** | Synthetic patient cohorts with known cluster structure for pipeline validation. MIMIC-IV (PhysioNet) provides realistic ICU data for development. Never use real PHI without IRB approval. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | SageMaker ml.m5.4xlarge notebook: ~$1/hr. Training jobs (ml.m5.4xlarge): ~$1/hr per job, typically 10-50 jobs per experiment cycle. S3 storage: negligible. Glue ETL: ~$0.44/DPU-hour. Monthly estimate: $200-2,000 depending on iteration frequency. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Notebooks for exploration; training jobs for clustering; experiments for tracking |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Data lake: raw clinical data, feature matrices, cluster results, validation outputs |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Glue** | ETL pipeline: source system extraction, feature engineering, cohort assembly |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Athena** | Ad-hoc SQL exploration of feature matrices and cohort characteristics |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption key management for all data at rest |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Job monitoring, failure alerting, cost tracking |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **SageMaker Experiments** | Systematic tracking of clustering runs, parameters, and results |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 1: Cohort assembly and feature extraction.** Before any clustering happens, you need to define exactly which patients are in your study and what features describe them. This is the most time-consuming step and the one that determines whether your results are meaningful. The cohort definition includes inclusion criteria (confirmed diagnosis, minimum observation period, minimum data completeness), exclusion criteria (pediatric patients if studying adult disease, patients with confounding comorbidities), and a time window (features measured over what period). Get this wrong and your clusters will reflect data quality differences, not disease biology.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION assemble_cohort(disease_code, min_observation_months, min_data_completeness):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Define the study population with rigorous inclusion/exclusion criteria.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Every decision here affects downstream results. Document everything.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Step 1a: Identify candidate patients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     candidates = query patients with:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         - at least 2 encounters with diagnosis code = disease_code
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         - first diagnosis at least min_observation_months ago
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         - age >= 18 at first diagnosis (adult cohort)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Step 1b: Apply data completeness filter
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Patients with very sparse data will cluster together based on missingness,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // not biology. Remove them or impute carefully.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     eligible = filter candidates where:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         - proportion of non-missing lab values >= min_data_completeness
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         - at least 3 clinical encounters in observation window
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         - not deceased within 30 days of first diagnosis (survivorship bias)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Step 1c: Extract feature matrix
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Each row = one patient. Each column = one clinical feature.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features = FOR each patient in eligible:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         extract:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             - demographics: age_at_diagnosis, sex, bmi
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             - lab_values: mean, trend, variability for each relevant lab
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             - vitals: mean, trend for BP, HR, SpO2, etc.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             - medications: binary flags for medication classes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             - comorbidities: binary flags from problem list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             - utilization: ED_visits, hospitalizations, specialist_visits
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             - functional_status: if available (often missing)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN eligible, features
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 2: Feature preprocessing and dimensionality reduction.** Raw clinical features are messy. Labs have different scales (hemoglobin in g/dL vs. creatinine in mg/dL). Missing values are common and non-random (a missing HbA1c might mean the test wasn't ordered because diabetes wasn't suspected). Features may be highly correlated (systolic and diastolic BP). This step normalizes, imputes, and reduces the feature space to something clustering algorithms can work with effectively. Skip this and your clusters will be dominated by whichever feature has the largest numeric range.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION preprocess_features(feature_matrix):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Handle missing data. This is a critical decision point.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Options: mean/median imputation, multiple imputation, or missingness indicators.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // For subtype discovery, multiple imputation is preferred because it preserves
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // uncertainty. But for initial exploration, median imputation with a
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // missingness indicator column is a reasonable starting point.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each feature column:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF missing_rate > 0.5:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             DROP the column  // too sparse to be informative
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ELSE IF missing_rate > 0:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             imputed_values = median imputation (or KNN imputation for correlated features)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             ADD binary column: "{feature}_was_missing" = 1 where originally missing
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Normalize all features to zero mean, unit variance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Without this, features measured in larger units dominate distance calculations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     normalized = standardize each column to mean=0, std=1
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Reduce dimensionality. PCA for linear structure, UMAP for nonlinear.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Retain enough components to explain ~80-90% of variance (PCA)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // or use domain knowledge to select target dimensionality (UMAP).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     reduced = apply PCA retaining components explaining 85% of variance
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Alternative: UMAP with n_components=10 for nonlinear manifold
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN reduced, normalization_parameters
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 3: Consensus clustering.** This is the core discovery step. Rather than running a single clustering algorithm once and trusting the result, consensus clustering runs the algorithm many times with different random subsamples and builds a consensus matrix showing how reliably each pair of patients clusters together. This separates robust structure from noise. The consensus matrix itself becomes the input to a final clustering step, producing clusters that are stable across perturbations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION consensus_clustering(feature_matrix, k_range, n_iterations):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Run clustering many times to assess stability.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // k_range: try multiple values of K (e.g., 2 through 8)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // n_iterations: how many bootstrap runs per K (typically 100-500)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     results_by_k = empty map
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each k in k_range:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Initialize consensus matrix: N_patients x N_patients, all zeros
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         consensus_matrix = zeros(n_patients, n_patients)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         indicator_matrix = zeros(n_patients, n_patients)  // tracks which pairs were sampled together
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR i = 1 to n_iterations:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Subsample 80% of patients (without replacement)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             subsample_indices = random_sample(80% of patient indices)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             subsample_data = feature_matrix[subsample_indices]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Cluster the subsample
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             labels = run_clustering(subsample_data, k=k, algorithm="kmeans")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Alternative algorithms: GMM, spectral, hierarchical
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Update consensus matrix: for each pair of subsampled patients,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // record whether they were assigned to the same cluster
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             FOR each pair (a, b) in subsample_indices:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 indicator_matrix[a, b] += 1  // they were both in this subsample
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 IF labels[a] == labels[b]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     consensus_matrix[a, b] += 1  // and they clustered together
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Normalize: proportion of times each pair clustered together
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // (out of times they were both sampled)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         consensus_proportion = consensus_matrix / indicator_matrix
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Final clustering on the consensus matrix itself
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         final_labels = run_clustering(consensus_proportion, k=k, algorithm="hierarchical")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Compute quality metrics for this K
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         silhouette = compute_silhouette_score(consensus_proportion, final_labels)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         pac = compute_proportion_ambiguous_clustering(consensus_proportion)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // PAC: proportion of pairs with consensus between 0.1 and 0.9
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Lower PAC = cleaner separation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         results_by_k[k] = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             labels: final_labels,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             consensus_matrix: consensus_proportion,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             silhouette: silhouette,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             pac: pac
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Select optimal K based on metrics (lowest PAC, highest silhouette, clinical sense)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     optimal_k = select_k(results_by_k)  // often requires human judgment
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN results_by_k[optimal_k], results_by_k
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 4: Stability validation.** Even with consensus clustering, you need to verify that the discovered clusters are stable. This step uses bootstrap resampling of the full dataset and measures how consistently patients are assigned to the same cluster across resamples. Clusters that fragment or merge under resampling are not robust enough to call subtypes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION validate_stability(feature_matrix, cluster_labels, n_bootstrap):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Assess whether clusters are robust to data perturbation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // If removing 20% of patients changes the cluster structure,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // the clusters are not real subtypes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     reference_labels = cluster_labels
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     stability_scores = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR i = 1 to n_bootstrap:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Resample with replacement (standard bootstrap)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         bootstrap_indices = sample_with_replacement(n_patients)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    300[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         bootstrap_data = feature_matrix[bootstrap_indices]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Re-cluster the bootstrap sample
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         bootstrap_labels = run_clustering(bootstrap_data, k=optimal_k)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Measure agreement with reference clustering
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    306[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // (only for patients that appear in both)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Adjusted Rand Index: 1.0 = perfect agreement, 0.0 = random
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ari = adjusted_rand_index(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             reference_labels[bootstrap_indices],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    310[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             bootstrap_labels
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         stability_scores.append(ari)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     mean_stability = mean(stability_scores)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Interpretation:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // > 0.8: highly stable clusters (good candidate subtypes)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    317[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // 0.6-0.8: moderately stable (proceed with caution)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // < 0.6: unstable (likely not real subtypes)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    320[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN mean_stability, stability_scores
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    322[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 5: Clinical characterization.** This is where statistics meets medicine. For each discovered cluster, compute the distinguishing clinical features, demographic profiles, and (critically) outcomes. The goal is to translate "Cluster 3" into "patients with predominantly inflammatory markers, younger onset, rapid progression, and poor response to standard bronchodilators." Without this translation, the clusters are useless to clinicians.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION characterize_clusters(patients, features, labels, outcomes):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // For each cluster, build a clinical profile that a physician can interpret.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     cluster_profiles = empty map
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each cluster_id in unique(labels):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         cluster_patients = patients where labels == cluster_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Demographics
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         demographics = compute:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             - mean age, age distribution
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             - sex ratio
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             - race/ethnicity distribution
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             - mean BMI
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Distinguishing features (what makes this cluster different)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Use statistical tests comparing this cluster vs. all others
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         distinguishing = FOR each feature:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             compute effect_size (Cohen's d for continuous, odds ratio for binary)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             compute p_value (t-test or chi-square, with multiple testing correction)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             KEEP features where adjusted_p < 0.05 AND abs(effect_size) > 0.5
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Outcomes (the clinical validation)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         outcomes_profile = compute:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             - mortality rate (1-year, 5-year)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             - hospitalization rate
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             - disease progression rate
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             - treatment response rates (by medication class)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             - time to first exacerbation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Characteristic feature ranking (top 5-10 features that define this cluster)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         top_features = rank distinguishing features by absolute effect size, take top 10
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         cluster_profiles[cluster_id] = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             n_patients: count(cluster_patients),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             proportion: count(cluster_patients) / total_patients,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             demographics: demographics,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             distinguishing_features: distinguishing,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             top_features: top_features,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             outcomes: outcomes_profile
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Statistical comparison across clusters
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Are outcomes significantly different between clusters?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     outcome_differences = FOR each outcome metric:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         run Kruskal-Wallis test (or log-rank for survival) across clusters
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         report p_value and effect_size
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN cluster_profiles, outcome_differences
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    375[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    376[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    377[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 6: External validation.** The ultimate test. Apply the clustering model (or a classifier trained on the discovered clusters) to a completely independent dataset. If the same subtypes appear with similar characteristics, you have something real. If they don't replicate, go back to the drawing board.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    378[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    379[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION external_validation(trained_model, external_dataset):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Apply the subtype model to data it has never seen.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    382[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This is the difference between a finding and a discovery.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Option A: Apply the same clustering to external data
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    385[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     external_features = preprocess(external_dataset, using same normalization_parameters)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     external_labels = assign_clusters(external_features, trained_model)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    388[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Option B: Train a classifier on discovered subtypes, apply to external data
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // (more practical for deployment)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     classifier = train_random_forest(features=training_features, labels=cluster_labels)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     external_labels = classifier.predict(external_features)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Validate: do external clusters have the same clinical characteristics?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     external_profiles = characterize_clusters(external_dataset, external_features, external_labels)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Compare profiles between discovery and validation cohorts
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     replication_score = FOR each cluster:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         compare top_features between discovery and validation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         compare outcome_profiles between discovery and validation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         compute correlation of effect sizes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Interpretation:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // High correlation of effect sizes across cohorts = replicating subtypes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Low correlation = overfitting to discovery cohort
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN external_labels, external_profiles, replication_score
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter06.08-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Expected Results
