[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    480[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    481[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Performance benchmarks:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    482[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    483[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Metric | Typical Value |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    484[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |--------|---------------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    485[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Cohort assembly (Glue ETL) | 15-45 minutes for 100K patients |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    486[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Feature preprocessing | 5-10 minutes |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    487[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Consensus clustering (500 iterations, K=2-8) | 30-120 minutes on ml.m5.4xlarge |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    488[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Stability validation (200 bootstraps) | 20-60 minutes |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    489[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Clinical characterization | 5-10 minutes |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    490[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | End-to-end single experiment | 2-4 hours |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    491[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Typical experiments before publishable result | 20-50 iterations over weeks |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    492[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    493[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Where it struggles:** Diseases with continuous spectra rather than discrete subtypes (the clusters are real but the boundaries are arbitrary). Small cohorts (under 500 patients) where statistical power is insufficient. Datasets with high missingness where imputation choices dominate the cluster structure. Multi-site data where site effects create artificial clusters.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    494[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    495[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    496[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    497[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Honest Take
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    498[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    499[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Here's what nobody tells you about disease subtype discovery until you've done it three times:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    500[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    501[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The algorithm will always find clusters. Always. You can feed it random noise and it will partition it into groups with high silhouette scores. The hard part is not finding clusters. The hard part is convincing yourself (and reviewers, and clinicians) that the clusters are real.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    502[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    503[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The feature selection step is where 80% of the intellectual work happens. I've seen projects where changing from "mean lab values" to "lab value trajectories" completely changed the discovered subtypes. Both sets of subtypes were statistically valid. Only one was clinically meaningful. You cannot outsource this decision to the algorithm.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    504[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    505[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Stability is your best friend. If your clusters survive bootstrap resampling, subsampling, algorithm changes, and feature perturbation, they're probably real. If they fragment when you sneeze at the data, they're not. I've learned to run stability analysis before I even look at the clinical characterization. It saves the heartbreak of falling in love with a beautiful cluster profile that turns out to be an artifact.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    506[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    507[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The publication bias in this field is severe. Nobody publishes "we clustered 5,000 diabetes patients and found nothing meaningful." But that's the outcome of most attempts. Set expectations accordingly with your clinical collaborators.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    508[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    509[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The most common failure mode I've seen: clusters that are really just "sick patients vs. less sick patients" dressed up as subtypes. Severity is the dominant axis of variation in almost any clinical dataset. If your Cluster 1 is "sicker on every metric" and Cluster 2 is "healthier on every metric," you've rediscovered severity stratification, not subtypes. True subtypes should have crossing patterns: Cluster A is worse on some metrics but better on others.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    510[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    511[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    512[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    513[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Variations and Extensions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    514[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    515[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Temporal subtype discovery.** Instead of clustering patients at a single time point, cluster disease trajectories. Use dynamic time warping or hidden Markov models to find groups of patients with similar progression patterns. This captures the reality that subtypes may manifest differently over time, and patients may transition between subtypes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    516[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    517[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-modal integration.** Combine clinical features with genomic data (SNPs, gene expression), imaging features (radiomics from CT scans), and patient-reported outcomes. Methods like Similarity Network Fusion create a unified patient similarity network from heterogeneous data types. The subtypes discovered from integrated data are often more biologically grounded than those from clinical data alone.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    518[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    519[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Subtype-specific treatment response prediction.** Once subtypes are validated, build supervised models within each subtype to predict treatment response. This is the path from "we found subtypes" to "we can use subtypes to guide treatment." The clinical impact is in this second step, not the discovery itself.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    520[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    521[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    522[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    523[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Related Recipes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    524[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    525[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 6.4 (Disease Severity Stratification):** Simpler version that stratifies within a disease by severity rather than discovering novel subtypes. Use as a baseline to ensure your subtypes aren't just severity tiers.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    526[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 6.6 (Patient Similarity for Care Planning):** Uses similar distance metrics but for individual patient matching rather than population-level subtype discovery.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    527[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 6.10 (Multi-Morbidity Pattern Discovery):** Related approach applied to condition co-occurrence patterns rather than within-disease heterogeneity.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    528[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 7.4 (Disease Progression Prediction):** Consumes discovered subtypes as features for predicting individual patient trajectories.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    529[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    530[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
